## Scope

This slice delivers the first tranche of the Part J UX shell — the surfaces that are mostly UI/plumbing over capabilities the engine already has: the [Core] to-scale schematic cross-section (J.1), the [Standard] repeat/period unit-cell builder (J.2), the [Standard] code-defined stack templates (J.3), [Standard] drag-and-drop of library materials onto layer rows (J.4), and the [Standard] multi-system comparison workspace (J.5). Each reads from canonical domain values and delegates real work to a seam owned elsewhere rather than reinventing it.

UI-touching. J.3 templates load through the Part I `openProject` seam (slice 003) so schema validation (§A.7) applies uniformly. J.4 drag-drop resolves the dropped `materialEntry` id to `OpticalProperties` via Part D's material-resolution function (slice 004), never re-resolving dispersion. J.5 workspace owns layout/selection state only and delegates the actual multi-curve overlay to Part H §H.4 / `plotComparison` (slice 012). The schematic and repeat builder are pure projections/expansions provable headless. This slice relies on the slice-001 buildable FuncUI interpretation (public MIT `Avalonia.FuncUI` NuGet, NOT the audit-gated clone).

## Requirements

### R-1. §J.1 Schematic cross-section view [Core]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Schematic` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Schematic.fs`) that renders a single `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`) as a vertical, drawn-to-scale cross-section on an Avalonia `Canvas`, color-coded by material, with per-layer thickness labels and the incident-light ray drawn at its angle. The renderer MUST read its geometry only from the canonical domain values and MUST NOT introduce a parallel geometry model:

1. The film stack MUST be drawn from `OpticalSystem.films : List<Layer>` (`Media.fs:98`) top-to-bottom in list order; each band's drawn height MUST be a monotonic function of that layer's `Thickness` (`Media.fs:12`), where `Thickness.Thickness d` carries `d : double<meter>` and `Thickness.Infinity` (the half-space case) MUST be drawn as a fixed-height "semi-infinite" band, not scaled.
2. Thickness labels MUST be formatted in the layer's per-element default unit (the `unitOfMeasure` carried by the project per §A.7), converting from the stored `double<meter>` to the display unit ONLY here at the view boundary (§A.3) using the Part D `Units.fs` conversion seam (§D.2) over the engine constants `nmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`mmToMeter` (`Constants.fs:27,30,33`); Å and eV/cm⁻¹ conversions reuse the same §A.10 boundary helpers. No converted value MAY be written back into the model.
3. The upper and lower half-spaces MUST be drawn from `OpticalSystem.upper` / `OpticalSystem.lower : OpticalProperties` (`Media.fs:97,100`) as labelled incident/exit medium bands.
4. When `OpticalSystem.substrate` is `Some (Substrate.Plate _ | Substrate.Wedge _)` (`Media.fs:99`, `Substrate` `Media.fs:40`), the substrate MUST be drawn as a distinct band; for `Substrate.Wedge w` the band MUST be drawn with a non-parallel lower edge whose slope is taken from the wedge's `WedgeAngle` (`Fields.fs:328`, reached via `w.angle`), making the wedge visually distinct from a plate.
5. The incident-light ray MUST be drawn as a line entering the upper medium at the angle from the active source's `IncidentLightInfo.incidenceAngle` (`Fields.fs:342`); the ray's reflected and transmitted continuations MUST be indicated at the top film interface only (full per-interface beam tracing is owned by Part B's beam tree and MUST NOT be re-derived here).
6. Material color MUST be assigned by a deterministic, pure function of a material's stable identity key (the `materialEntry` id from §A.7), so the same material is the same color across redraws; the color table is a static map in `Schematic.fs` and MUST NOT be a config knob.

Caching of rendered geometry, retained-mode scene graphs, and an abstraction over the drawing backend are OUT OF SCOPE; the view MUST be a pure `OpticalSystem -> Avalonia control` projection re-evaluated by the MVU `view` (Part A §A.6 / 010 Part III §3).

### R-2. §J.2 Repeat / period unit-cell builder [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `RepeatBuilder` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/RepeatBuilder.fs`) that lets the user define a unit cell as an ordered list of `Layer` values (`Media.fs:24`) and a positive integer repeat count, and expands it into a flat `List<Layer>` suitable for assignment to `OpticalSystem.films` (`Media.fs:98`). The expansion MUST be the pure function `expand : Layer list -> int -> Layer list` implemented as `List.replicate count cell |> List.concat`; it MUST NOT introduce a new "super-layer" or "period" domain type, and the expanded films MUST be ordinary `Layer` records indistinguishable from manually entered ones. The builder is the [Standard] DBR/Bragg/EUV-Mo–Si convenience from 010 Part II §1; it MUST reject a repeat count `< 1` through the J.9 validation seam rather than silently clamping. The J.9 validation seam (`Validation.fs`) is owned by slice 015 (§J.9); to avoid an F# forward reference that would fail the `build`/`constructor-unit-tests` gates — the arc-runner runs one round per slice, so a later-slice symbol is not yet compiled when slice 014 builds — `RepeatBuilder.expand` itself MUST remain the pure `List.replicate count cell |> List.concat` with NO dependency on `Validation.fs`. The `R < 1` rejection is enforced by the slice-015 J.9 validator at the caller boundary, and its assertion is owned and tested in slice 015's `ValidationTests.fs` (AC-J9), NOT in slice 014. Storing the unfactored period as a separate serialized structure is OUT OF SCOPE — the project persists only the expanded `films` per §A.7.

### R-3. §J.3 Stack templates & wizards [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Templates` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Templates.fs`) exposing a fixed, code-defined set of starting designs — AR coating, bandpass filter, beam splitter, polarizer, waveplate, DBR — each a pure function `unit -> OpticalConstructorProject` (the root aggregate from §A.7) that pre-populates a starting design and is then handed to the ordinary editors. Each template MUST build its stack from real `Layer`/`OpticalSystem` values (`Media.fs:24,94`) and, where it needs a periodic structure (DBR), MUST call `RepeatBuilder.expand` (J.2) rather than duplicating that logic. Templates MUST NOT read from disk, MUST NOT be user-editable template files, and MUST NOT introduce a template-definition schema — they are F# literals. Loading a template MUST go through the same project-open path as a normal project (Part I §I.3 `openProject`) so schema validation (§A.7) applies uniformly.

### R-4. §J.4 Drag-and-drop of library items onto layers [Standard]

The Ui project MUST wire Avalonia drag-and-drop so a material from the materials library panel (Part D) dropped onto a layer row replaces that layer's `Layer.properties : OpticalProperties` (`Media.fs:26`) with the dragged material's resolved `OpticalProperties` (`MaterialProperties.fs:165`), leaving `Layer.thickness` unchanged. The drop payload MUST carry only the stable `materialEntry` id (§A.7), and resolution to `OpticalProperties` MUST go through Part D's material-resolution function — the named `resolveMaterial` by-id seam owned by slice 004 (§D.8), which evaluates the entry's dispersion at the active `WaveLength` — Part J MUST NOT re-resolve dispersion models or rebuild tensors. The drop MUST emit a single MVU message that the owning `update` applies immutably (producing a new `Layer`), consistent with the Part A MVU contract; no in-place mutation of the model is permitted (§0 constraint 1, immutable structures).

### R-5. §J.5 Multi-system comparison workspace [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Workspace` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Workspace.fs`) that holds several `OpticalSystem` values side by side for comparison, each addressed by the project's system collection (`OpticalConstructorProject.systems`, §A.7). For overlaying their computed curves the workspace MUST call the engine's existing comparison plot `plotComparison` (`Charting.fs:38`) — surfaced through the Part H §H.4 ScottPlot overlay rather than the engine's terminal `Chart.show` — which already accepts a `list<FixedInfo>` and plots model-by-model; Part J MUST NOT implement its own multi-curve overlay. The workspace owns layout and selection state only (which systems are visible, which is active); the actual chart surface is Part H's. Holding more than the systems already present in the open `OpticalConstructorProject` — e.g. a separate comparison document format — is OUT OF SCOPE.

## Non-requirements

- The favorites board / preferences / theme & dockable panels / validation seam implementation are Part J §J.6–J.9, owned by slice 015. J.2's reject-of-`count<1` is enforced by the slice-015 J.9 validator and tested in slice 015's `ValidationTests.fs` (AC-J9); slice 014's `RepeatBuilder.fs` and `RepeatBuilderTests.fs` MUST NOT reference `Validation.fs` (no forward reference into a later slice's module, which the one-round-per-slice arc-runner could not compile).
- The long-running job runner, in-app help/glossary/gallery, and the 3D system/beam view are Part J §J.10–J.12, owned by slice 016. The `SystemView3D`/AC-J12 portion of the `SchematicGeometryTests.fs` bullet (`.spec-md:993`) is owned by slice 016; only the schematic (AC-J1) portion of that bullet lands here.
- The multi-curve overlay implementation itself is Part H §H.4 (slice 012); J.5 only delegates to it via `plotComparison`.
- The Part D material-resolution function J.4 calls — the named `resolveMaterial` by-id seam — is owned by slice 004 (§D.8); J.4 only consumes it.
- The schema-validated `openProject` seam J.3 templates load through is owned by slice 003; this slice routes through it, it does not implement it.

